results.notes:
Here in the field (Pittsburgh) I would call these the classic Baorangia bicolor that seems to be so common out in CT and MA.

I have seen them around here before but they aren’t very common. Much less dense than I associate with the pallidorosea. Those have a texture that hugs a knife like cutting through a hunk of supermarket Colby cheese. This texture is more like classic boletes such as the Tylopilus.

They cap color fades from red to brown. No pink tones at all. The bug holes, common in some specimens, are very red.

These also show much deeper bluing on the pores and a more distinct color line between cap and stipe flesh. White mycelium rather than pale yellow. No particular odor or flavor except a lingering, gentle sweetness on the tip of my tongue.

results.notes: These popped up across a local park where I picked many Psilocybe ovoidecocystidiata last year. The town put a few inches of new “mulch” debris on top in April, and these started popping up all over the place in June/July. I say “mulch” because it’s woody debris mixed with pieces of garbage (lol) and probably plenty of composted waste, so realistically the substrate could be anything woody or compost-related, but not grass/lawns. I’ve seen several observations on here that are macroscopically identical being called P. cinctulus, P. olivaceous, P. fraxinophilus, P. fimicola etc. but a google searched also turned up the name P. atrobalteatus (which may or may not be defunct, Unsure). Clusters were widespread across the substrate, not in isolated areas.

sweet nutty smell.

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collection made by numerous foray participants. There were at least two dozen fruiting bodies on the ID tables, easily making it the second very common species at this foray in addition to Xanthoconim affine. I took several mushrooms home, but wound up not saving them as I had already sequenced an earlier exemplar of this species from Meadowoods, obs 210721.
Phylogenetically, B. vermiculosoides — if that’s what this critter is — belongs to Neoboletus. It is very closely related to Boletus brunneopanoides, a red-pored bolete described in 2007 from the Caribbean region, as well as another cryptic species found in the Sky Islands of AZ (see Terri Clement’s posts), both of which might turn out to be isolated populations or of vermiculosoides in the process of speciation. So far genetic evidence from a number of sequenced eastern collections indicates that we don’t have any genetically distinct lookalikes in this part of the country.

Cap up to 6 cm in diameter. Buff tannish, light (hard rain last night possibly washed out pigment). Becoming cracked with age, convex opening to become widely convex. Margin folds in towards pore surface when young, material remaining on margin in older specimens but worn off in oldest.
